   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "eng-4class-bss-md",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Random Forest with balanced_subsample — 4-class"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "b4c131a8-df2b-4484-9c6c-0c9c5c0849cc",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### balanced_subsample -- CLASS IMBALANCE HANDLING\n",
    "We use class_weight=\"balanced_subsample\" to address class imbalance in the poverty_risk_score labels. Random Forest trains each tree on a bootstrap sample of the training data (a resampled subset). With \"balanced_subsample\", sklearn recomputes class weights separately for each tree based on that tree’s bootstrap sample class distribution.\n",
    "Strengths:\n",
    " - More robust when bootstrap samples have slightly different class proportions (weights adapt per tree).\n",
    " - Often a bit more stable / less aggressive than global reweighting, reducing the risk of over-correcting.\n",
    " - Can work well when you want imbalance handling but still want the forest to reflect natural variationacross bootstrap samples.\n",
    "Weaknesses / tradeoffs:\n",
    " - Because weights vary per tree and can be less aggressive overall, minority-class precision/recall gains\n",
    "   may be smaller than with global \"balanced\".\n",
    " - If minority classes are consistently under-predicted, this approach may not push the model enough.\n",
    "Practical expectation: Tends to improve minority sensitivity compared to no weighting, while being somewhat conservative.\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 4,
   "id": "6ea59a66-0f0a-4485-b5f9-2267fb907f95",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "from sklearn.ensemble import RandomForestClassifier\n",
    "from sklearn.metrics import classification_report, confusion_matrix"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 5,
   "id": "eng-4class-bss",
   "metadata": {},
